<TEXT>
burmas military government has 
reimposed a ban on the issuing of visas to foreign journalists just 
months after relaxing restrictions in force for more than a quarter 
century 
a telexed message received by a bangkokbased journalist from the 
ministry of foreign affairs in rangoon said visas were temporarily 
suspended for journalists because of adverse news reports on burma 
by visiting correspondents 
the text dated july 4 was made available to the associated 
press on tuesday 
due to the fact that some correspondents have given adverse 
reports on the situation in myanmar burma weve temporarily 
suspended issuance of visas to foreign correspondents for the time 
being said a telex from ohn kyaw director general of the 
ministry of foreign affairs in rangoon 
other bangkokbased journalists said they had received similar 
responses to applications for visas from burmas embassy in bangkok 
burma rarely issued visas to foreign journalists after xenophobic 
socialist strongman ne win took power in 1962 
last year many foreign correspondents travelled to burma 
unofficially on tourist visas to cover a national uprising for 
democracy 
burma suspended the issuing of tourist visas shortly before the 
army began to crack down on the mass demonstrations killing 
thousands of people 
but after antigovernment dissent was crushed restrictions on 
press visits were relaxed in an effort to demonstate a new policy of 
openness and to counter persistant allegations of human rights 
abuses 
the restrictions on press visits have resurfaced at a time when 
the pace of political dissent has once again begun to quicken 
opposition groups have defied martial law regulations and staged 
large rallies demanding democratic rights and an end to military 
rule 
aung myint head of the visa section of the bangkok embassy said 
that the embassy was still accepting applications for visas from 
foreign correspondents but he was unable to say whether they would 
be approved 
officials at the ministry of foreign affairs in rangoon were also 
unable to clarify the position regarding visas for journalists 
but one official explained that the military government was 
annoyed that visiting journalists had interviewed opposition leaders 
while ignoring government officials he asked not to be identified 
by name 
a representative of a travel agency in bangkok that regularly 
arranges visits to burma said visas were still being issued to 
businessmen individual tourists and to those travelling in groups 
but all visitors were obliged to arrange a set itinerary with the 
state tourism office she said 
</TEXT>
