<TEXT>
erich honeckers sudden illness has 
provoked speculation about who is next in line for the east german 
communist leadership analysts say whoever succeeds the hardline 
honecker will face powerful pressure to embrace reforms 
honecker 76 was released from a hospital on monday after 
treatment for a gallstone over the weekend the official news agency 
adn said he had left a warsaw pact meeting in romania for treatment 
honecker who supervised the building of the berlin wall became 
party leader in 1971 and under his guidance east germany developed 
the soviet blocs most successful economy 
but honecker has rejected the political and economic reforms 
sweeping across the soviet union poland and hungary 
east germany has expressed deep concern over the swift pace of 
political change in hungary warning that opposition forces are 
trying to oust the communist party from the power 
at the same time however there have been growing street 
protests by east german demonstrators calling for more democracy 
western anaylsts expect an intense power struggle once honecker 
is no longer in control but they are pessimistic any of the current 
likely contenders would launch immediate reforms that would create a 
substantially freer east germany which remains one of the most 
rigidly controlled states in the soviet bloc 
there is no full member of the politburo who understands the 
need for political changes in east germany said eberhard 
schneider an expert on east german affairs at the federal institute 
for eastern and international studies in cologne 
they dont understand it and they dont want to he told the 
associated press on tuesday 
schneider and other observers say its only a matter of time 
before east germany recognizes it must change its ways if only for 
the sake of keeping up with reformist countries like hungary and 
poland that are attracting western investment interest 
the reforming european states in eastern europe will be better 
partners its just easier to cooperate with more open societies 
said peter danylow an east bloc expert at the german foundation for 
the study of foreign policy in bonn thats a point which should be 
clear to east germany 
when honecker is gone the analysts say the prospects of seeing 
reformminded communist party members climb to higher positions of 
power could dramatically improve 
danylow and other experts say its uncertain who would follow 
honecker but point out some major contenders 
the most apparent is egon krenz a 52yearold member of the 
policymaking politburo and secretary for security matters in the 
central committee a powerful position and one held by honecker 
before he took over in 1971 
krenz represented honecker on some official visits that is an 
important symbol of power schneider said 
another prospect is guenter schabowsky 60 who holds the key 
post of communist party chief in berlin 
i dont think anything major would occur under krenz but 
perhaps schabowsky has a little more understanding for what needs to 
be done schneider told the ap 
the masscirculation west german newspaper bild said monday that 
another possible candidate is siegfried lorenz the 59yearold 
party chief in the city of karlmarxstadt 
the politburo has recently stepped up criticism of reformers 
within party ranks 
in one of the sharpest official rebukes in a decade the 
politburo denounced dresdens party leadership as ineffective in 
controlling hostile bourgeois activities a reference to growing 
street protests by human rights activists for more democracy 
the 61yearold dresden party chief hans modrow is believed to 
have a sympathetic view of soviet president mikhail s gorbachevs 
reforms 
schneider said honeckers departure could boost the careers of 
reformminded officials like modrow 
he said there was a crop of younger officials not yet in 
positions of real power who have a keen sense of the need for major 
changes 
there are some very good people who understand the problems 
the party must give these people the chance to get to the top 
schneider said 
</TEXT>
