the third tropical depression of the atlantic 
hurricane season formed off the coast of africa but showed no signs 
of growing into a tropical storm forecasters said tuesday 
at 1030 pm edt tuesday the depression packed maximum 
sustained winds of 35 mph and was located about 625 miles 
eastnortheast of the northern leeward islands forecasters said 
the depressions center was located near 215 degrees north 
latitude and 54 degrees west longitude and was moving 
westnorthwest towards the lesser antilles at 13 mph said 
forecaster hal gerrish at the national hurricane center in suburban 
coral gables 
the depression which formed late monday night was not expected 
to strengthen significantly wednesday clark said 
if the depression gathers sustained winds of 39 mph it would be 
named tropical storm barry tropical storm allison the first named 
storm of the season caused widespread flood damage in texas last 
month 
