the market on nearby dimitrov square the same one where british 
prime minister margaret thatcher purchased garlic and peppers on a 
1983 visit 
bush had sweeter fare in mind a dozen ripe peaches that cost 18 
hungarian forints a kilo or about 14 cents a pound 
that was cheap for the president of the united states but close 
to an hours wage for the average hungarian 
i recommend these to you he told reporters who trailed him 
through the crowd of shoppers and vendors 
an ebullient bush shook hands and signed autographs for the 
crowd and blew kisses with his hand 
he was greeted with applause wherever he went in the ornate 
wrought iron market built late in the 19th century where vendors 
sell succulent heaps of fruit vegetables meat and other produce 
from hungarys rich farming land 
