defense secretary dick cheney says he has no 
magic formula to eliminate fraud and waste from pentagon purchasing 
but he believes his new reorganization plan can save taxpayers at 
least 30 billion by 1993 
cheneys plan unveiled tuesday includes proposals to reduce the 
number of individuals involved in purchasing decisions by the 
thousands and to limit the authority of individual military services 
to complete deals 
still cheney told reporters theres no silver bullet here 
we have a blueprint that we plan to pursue to try to 
significantly improve the way we do business he said if were 
going to be successful it will be because we got congress to 
cooperate 
cheney acted immediately to reorganize his toplevel management 
team but other parts of his plan will need congressional approval 
his report was requested by president bush five months ago in 
response to weapons procurement scandals that have rocked the 
pentagon in the last two years 
federal prosecutors ill wind investigation has focused on 
bribery by consultants who sought inside information for their 
clients on pending military contracts 
cheney said central to his plan is giving the undersecretary of 
defense increased authority over purchasing decisions by the 
individual services he said he intends to eliminate several layers 
of top management to establish a clear chain of command on such 
decisions 
