<TEXT>
the french appeals court has refused to allow two 
homosexual couples to enjoy the same rights as those given to 
unmarried heterosexual couples living together 
the judgment of the court published tuesday invalidated the 
decision of lower courts in the two cases the decision cannot be 
appealed further 
in one case an air france flight attendant identified as yves 
surnames were withheld demanded that his livein companion serge 
be granted reduced fares and other benefits that air france grants 
to employees living with members of the opposite sex 
in the second case the mother of three children nadia set up 
house with her friend annie and sought to obtain health insurance 
for annie from the social security administration she was turned 
down on the ground that french legislation concerning unmarried 
cohabitation applies only to men and women 
the appeals court ruling simultaneously on both cases said they 
did not fall within the law of january 2 1978 which defined the 
legal meaning of unmarried cohabitation 
this law the appeals court ruled concerned two people who have 
decided to live together as man and wife without the benefit of 
marriage and can therefore only concern a couple formed by a man 
and a woman 
