<TEXT>
the peace corps precedentsetting effort in 
hungary will send about 60 american volunteers there to train 
hungarians to teach english us officials said wednesday 
this is a historic day and the threshold of a new era for the 
united states peace corps said paul d coverdell director of the 
agency 
president bush announced the initiative the first peace corps 
program in a communist country during his visit to hungary 
the teaching of english is one of the most popular american 
exports bush said in budapest adding that the program will help 
open the global market to more hungarians 
coverdell speaking at a news conference here after bushs 
announcement said hungary will the 100th nation to be served by the 
peace corps 
it will also be the first european and first eastern bloc 
nation in which the peace corps has served he said 
the united states announced plans this spring to send peace corps 
volunteers to china but chinese officials have delayed the program 
in the wake of student unrest coverdell said the chinese have said 
they want to talk more about the program 
we are prepared to enter into those discussions on whatever 
timetable they choose he said wednesday 
more than 121000 volunteers have served in 99 developing 
countries over the last 28 years coverdell said adding that the 
program in hungary shows that the underlying mission of peace has no 
political or national boundaries 
president bush today told the hungarians that to succeed in 
reforms you need partners not just governments but people 
coverdell said the united states peace corps is proud to provide 
some of those partners 
a formal agreement still needs to be worked out with hungarian 
officials and an assessment team will determine the size and scope 
of the initial program 
the first peace corps volunteers may arrive in hungary by late 
fall for training before being assigned to teaching positions early 
next year coverdell said the number of volunteers could reach 60 
by 1990 he said 
the emphasis will be on training hungarian teachers to teach 
english as a second language russianlanguage training is no longer 
required in hungarian schools and hungarian officials have 
expressed interest in expanding the use of english 
coverdell said he has had no discussions with officials of other 
soviet bloc countries about possible peace corps activities 
we are responding here to a very specific request from 
hungary he said 
more than 6000 peace corps volunteers work in 65 countries 
around the world providing assistance in agriculture education 
health natural resources conservation business skilled trades and 
other areas 
