<TEXT>
without a hint of remorse jerry adam 
stepped into the pristine hercules glade wilderness in the mark 
twain national forest and set a fire that blackened 1000 acres 
no one rushed to arrest him no smokejumpers parachuted in to 
fight the flames adam is a fire technician with the us forest 
service 
we do prescribed burns in the glade areas to reduce the amount 
of fuel that could lead to a major fire said forest service 
spokesman dave wester in other cases its done to provide a 
certain kind of habitat for wildlife we sometimes burn grazing land 
if it is seeded with warm season grasses since fire is part of the 
management of those grasses occasionally well burn to prepare a 
site for tree planting 
prescribed burning was conducted this spring on about 6000 acres 
in the 15millionacre mark twain national forest in southern 
missouri wester said the closely monitored burns are done just 
before trees and grasses turn green 
camping hiking and horseback riding are popular in the remote 
region classified by the government as having the cleanest air in 
the state the glades a unique combination of open grasslands 
featuring prairie vegetation shallow soil rocky outcroppings 
steep hillsides and forested knobs are also prized for dogwood 
blooms in the spring and outstanding fall foilage 
prescribed burning is necessary every three to five years in the 
glades adam said 
if it isnt done youll have a fuel buildup and the potential 
for a catastrophic fire which is what they had at yellowstone last 
year in which almost all living trees are killed and the soil is 
exposed and sterilized he said 
fire also keeps the spread of trees in check and gets rid of dead 
material that can choke young plants 
fire is also important to animals that live in the open glade 
landscape 
theres a couple of little critters that really depend on these 
glades such as the collared lizard and the roadrunner which is 
more common to the arid southwest adam said we have armadillos 
here too 
in missouri the rare bachman sparrow nests only in the hercules 
wilderness glade 
ash from the fires also rejuvenates dozens of varieties of 
wildflowers fire is just like giving them a shot of fertilizer 
adam said 
periodic fires once occurred naturally in the glades started by 
lightning or perhaps by indians adam said but when europeans moved 
in they put out the natural fires and built roads which acted as 
firebreaks 
it took a forest service crew using torches dripping a 
combination of diesel fuel and gasoline just five hours on a cool 
day in early april to burn the leafy groundcover off 1000 acres in 
the hercules glade wilderness 
today few signs remain of the fire dense green prairie grasses 
and wildflowers are abundant the fire burned to a height of about 
three or four feet blackening the bark of tall hardy oak and pine 
trees but otherwise not harming them 
adam doubts that any animals died in the fire 
a turtle will scoot under those leaves for safety and the fire 
will run right over him he said as soon as the fire passes by 
and cools down youll see all these little lizards come out of 
their holes of course the bigger animals like deer and turkey 
just move out 
</TEXT>
