<TEXT>
a delegation of american mental health experts 
who visited the soviet union said wednesday that more reforms are 
needed to prevent hospitalization of dissidents and other citizens 
who arent mentally ill 
the recommendation was one of several the group made to protect 
people against abuse by soviet psychiatric institutions 
the soviets disagreed with some aspects of the study but 
nonetheless called it a valuable and useful document 
the official 26member delegation was invited to visit the soviet 
union from feb 26 to march 12 to assess recent changes in soviet 
psychiatry they examined 15 patients and 12 former patients who had 
been released within the preceding two years 
the visit came amid allegations of psychiatric abuses in the 
soviet union one report had cited 346 cases of alleged abuse 
between 1977 and 1983 
but the american delegation said there had been progress in 
recent years toward establishing some legal protection for patients 
subject to forced confinement 
in its 117page report the delegation said broad concepts of 
social dangerousness have contributed to the soviet practice of 
hospitalizing people who arent mentally ill 
for this and other reasons the delegation recommends that 
additional steps be taken to revise the soviet criminal codes to 
remove all prohibitions against expression of political or religious 
beliefs it said 
in addition the report said new legislation or regulations 
appear necessary to limit involuntary hospitalizations solely to 
those who are a direct danger to themselves or others 
the report recommended increased use of defense lawyers to guard 
against patient abuse and the institutionalization of periodic 
reviews to ensure that hospital stays are not excessively long 
according to the report the soviets generally complied with the 
terms of the agreement under which the visit was made although 
there were some significant procedural obstacles that made 
completion more difficult 
the preliminary soviet response acknowledged the existence of 
such obstacles but said that problem by no means meant that the 
soviet specialists artificially created difficulties and tried to 
limit access to the necessary information on the patients 
as for the allegation by the us team that mental patients have 
insufficient legal protections the soviets said efforts were being 
made to conform soviet legislation to international standards 
in addition the soviets said there has been discussion about 
creating an independent commission to examine complaints and monitor 
institutions 
the soviet ministry of foreign affairs has been interested in 
inviting foreign psychiatrists to visit as part of growing soviet 
interest in improving international perception of its humanrights 
policy 
