<TEXT>
the boston ledger a weekly newspaper that combined 
folksy neighborhood news with tough political reporting has ceased 
publication after 52 years 
it was not an easy decision to make but the realities of 
business set in the advertising support was just not there 
publisher frederic n phinney said wednesday 
circulation of the tabloid which was distributed free had gone 
from 48000 in 1982 to 29000 this year 
in the same period advertising revenue fell about 40 percent and 
the staff was cut to two fulltime employees from a peak of eight 
phinney said 
the paper focused on events and personalities in boston 
neighborhoods it also covered the arts and politics and had 
something of a lovehate relationship with the administration of 
kevin white mayor from 1969 to 1985 
kevin white was a great booster of ours even though at times 
we kicked the living daylights out of him phinney said 
at its best the ledger was something of a cross between a 
neighborhood paper for back baybeacon hill and the village 
voice a paper that tried to take an iconoclastic view of life in 
the city added john van scoyoc who was the ledgers editor in 
the late 1970s and is now managing editor at wgbhtv 
the newspaper was founded in 1937 and was named the back bay 
ledgerbeacon hill times until phinney and his father bought it in 
1967 and changed the name to the boston ledger 
the phinney family company citizen group publications inc also 
publishes two paidcirculation weeklies the allstonbrighton 
citizen and the brookline citizen and a free weekly the 
charlestown ledger 
phinney said the boston ledgers losses had been draining the 
other papers which will continue to be published 
</TEXT>
