<TEXT>
a senate committee gave partyline approval 
wednesday to a measure by sen edward m kennedy to require american 
employers to provide health insurance to all their workers and their 
workers dependents 
the measure cleared kennedys labor and human resources committee 
on a 97 vote but is strongly opposed by the administration and 
other powerful groups including many business organizations 
coupled with special provisions for children the kennedy bill is 
intended to provide coverage for the estimated 37 million americans 
not now covered by any public or private health insurance 
although many of the details have been reworked the bill is 
similar to one that cleared the committee last year but was not 
considered in either the full senate or house 
kennedy noted that the majority of businesses already insure 
their workers yet twothirds of all the americans who lack basic 
health insurance protection are workers or members of working 
families 
for more than half a century we have required employers to pay 
a minimum wage to participate in social security to contribute to 
unemployment compensation and to purchase workmans compensation 
insurance the massachusetts democrat said at the outset of the 
committee markup session in 1989 it is time to require the 
provision of basic health insurance coverage as well 
labor secretary elizabeth dole arguing against the measure in a 
letter to kennedy said enactment of his bill would result in a 
significant loss of job opportunities impair our nations economic 
competitiveness and interfere with the right of employees and 
employers to determine between themselves the most appropriate 
compensation package to meet their circumstances 
the kennedy bill would require employers to pay at least 80 
percent of the insurance premiums for all employees who work at 
least 25 hours a week and 100 percent for those who do not make at 
least 25 percent above the minimum wage 
although employees would have to pay a larger share of the 
premium the health policy would have to be available to those who 
work between 17 and 25 hours a week 
the insurance package must include hospital care physician care 
diagnostic tests prenatal and wellbaby care and a limited mental 
health benefit deductibles could not exceed 250 per individual or 
500 per family 
among special provisions for small employers is a system of 
regional insurers to take advantage of group rates and a federal 
subsidy for those whose required premiums would exceed 5 percent of 
gross revenues of the business 
moreover small employers with fewer than 10 employees who have 
been in business less than two years would have to offer a lowcost 
insurance plan to their workers but would not have to help pay the 
premium finally the bill would be phased in over a fiveyear 
period for employers with five or fewer workers 
</TEXT>
