<TEXT>
republican whip new gingrich joined more than 
110 fellow house members wednesday in calling for expanded federal 
child care assistance that concentrates on tax credits rather than 
direct grants 
a democratic bill calling for direct grants has already passed 
the senate 
republican reps clyde holloway of louisiana and dick schulze of 
pennsylvania drafted the new legislation which gingrich said 
brought house republicans to a pretty unified position 
they drafters claim 115 cosponsors including about 20 democrats 
for the bill they introduced wednesday 
the republican measure would expand tax credits for both 
lowerand middleincome parents of children under 4 regardless of 
whether both parents actually work and pay for outside child care 
the democratic bill would made additional federal money available 
to states to make direct payments to day care providers and would 
establish nonbinding federal standards for child care providers 
the senate version widely known as the abc bill was 
primarily the work of sen chris dodd dconn 
gingrich expressed confidence that the gop congressmens 
approach similar to a proposal by president bush can prevail in 
the house if it gets a straight upordown vote in competition with 
the democratic version 
the american people desire to have no procedural games played 
with this said gingrich all were asking for is a straight up 
and down vote 
some democrats have said they would like to see the house child 
care legislation attached to an overall budget reconciliation 
measure a tactical move that could make it difficult to get a 
direct vote on the competing child care bills 
i cant believe the democrats would try to play that game 
said gingrich 
he said the way the child care legislation is handled by house 
leaders an issue not likely to be resolved until early fall will 
be a good measure of house speaker tom foleys stated intention to 
give republican initiatives a fair chance 
gingrich said the republican taxcredit approach is based on the 
premise that parents are inherently better at taking care of their 
children than bureaucrats and that women who choose to stay home 
to care for their young children should not be discriminated against 
he said the abc bill with its emphasis on uniform standards for 
child care providers makes an inherent automatic assumption that 
many parents are too dumb to choose child care for their children 
