a highway safety group and relatives of victims 
of a new york bridge collapse asked a court wednesday to block 
federal efforts to double the allowable time between bridge 
inspections 
less frequent bridge inspections mean more chances for bridge 
collapses said gerald donaldson a spokesman for the center for 
auto safety in announcing the lawsuit he said the federal highway 
administration is trifling with the lives of millions of 
americans 
the target of the lawsuit filed in us district court for the 
district of columbia seeks to invalidate a rule issued in august 
1988 by the fhwa 
the rule affecting some 122000 bridges nationwide allows 
states to apply for exemptions from the mandatory twoyear 
inspection cycle meaning the bridges are checked every four years 
instead 
kansas pennsylvania south dakota texas and washington have 
already sought to exempt more than 15000 bridges in those states 
the center said 
the suit argues that in making the new rule the fhwa failed to 
properly consider and evaluate the safety impact of the proposed 
changes and furthermore based its decision upon an invalid 
analysis of the regulations economic benefits 
it also charges that the agency failed to provide a reasoned 
basis for deciding to permit inspections every four years 
an fwha spokesman did not immediately return a phone call seeking 
comment on the lawsuit 
coplaintiffs are virginia hughes of troy ny whose husband 
donald was killed in the 1987 bridge collapse on the new york state 
thruway and william peck of schuylerville ny whose wife mary 
louise and daughter kristen died in the accident 
in january the center and the relatives filed a petition with 
the fhwa asking it to reconsider the rule a letter accompanying the 
petition pointed out that the national transportation safety board 
which also opposed the new rule cited insufficient state inspection 
practices as a major contributing factor to the collapse of the 
thruway bridge 
that span fell into the schoharie creek on april 5 1987 killing 
10 people a year later the chairman of the ntsb made an urgent 
call for highway bridge inspections noting that 43000 of the 
nations bridges had not been inspected within two years as required 
