<TEXT>
in a setback for the bush administration the 
senate foreign relations committee on wednesday shelved a bid to 
give us weapons to the noncommunist opposition in cambodia 
after that decision and several others the panel voted 170 to 
report to the senate floor a bill authorizing 116 billion in 
foreign aid for the next two fiscal years a period beginning next 
oct 1 
the panel took no action on the cambodia plan after several 
democrats voiced fears that any arms provided might find their way 
into the hands of the khmer rouge the cambodian faction blamed for 
the deaths of at least one million people when it held power during 
the 1970s 
the move by the committee does not necessarily kill the proposal 
senators said it might be renewed in the form of an amendment on the 
senate floor or during a conference with the house on its version of 
foreign aid authorization legislation 
the committee also voted to impose a 90 million cap on us 
military aid for the government of el salvador a move intended to 
symbolize fears that rightwing death squad activity might be 
renewed under that nations newly elected conservative government 
the action sparked a brief debate in which sen jesse helms 
rnc said the senate action would encourage communist insurgents 
inside el salvador 
