<TEXT>
with interest rates falling and stock prices 
rising mutualfund investors would seem to have a lot to applaud 
and little to complain about so far in 1989 
funds in nearly all categories of style and objective have posted 
robust gains since the start of the year helping to push echoes of 
the 1987 crash into distant memory 
an index of growth stock funds calculated by lipper analytical 
services inc reached a record high just a few weeks ago having 
recouped all its 1987 losses and then some 
bond and other income funds meanwhile have rallied sharply of 
late as falling interest rates pushed up the prices of the assets in 
their portfolios 
for the first half of the year according to lipper stock and 
other equity mutual funds averaged a return of 1275 percent 
fixedincome funds returned a lessimposing 692 percent but 
nearly all of that increase came in april may and june after 
interest rates started their descent holding out the promise of 
more good news should rates keep falling in the months ahead 
about the only two blots on the bright overall picture occurred 
in goldoriented funds which have been lagging for some time and 
international funds 
in the eyes of many analysts the weak showing of the gold funds 
betokened an absence of fears about inflation and other economic 
calamities that historically tend to drive up the price of gold 
international funds suffered as the dollar rallied against other 
leading currencies in foreign exchange markets 
the dollar was in demand for a change since it appeared that 
the us economy was heading for a relatively benign soft 
landing while other major industrialized countries struggled with 
increasing inflation and upward pressure on interest rates 
in other words even the poor performance of a few specialized 
sectors of the fund industry reflected seemingly favorable news for 
the overall us investment outlook 
so what could trouble a fund investor these days first of all 
there are those nagging doubts that positive results will be as easy 
to come by in the future as they have been in the recent past 
the equity funds gain the first half stretched out to an annual 
rate works out to about 31 percent noted a michael lipper 
president of lipper analytical thats at least twice the historical 
average 
or to put it another way the funds could achieve no progress at 
all in the second half and still wind up 1989 with results as good 
as they have shown in an average year in the past 
then too theres the question of relative fund performance as 
measured against a standard such as standard amp poors composite 
index of 500 stocks 
the firsthalf gain by the average fund fell short of the 1652 
percent advance posted by the sampp 500 assuming reinvestment of 
dividends 
to veteran fund investors this news is no shock over time in a 
world of hundreds of funds logic suggests that the typical fund 
cannot beat the market 
furthermore the funds results are held back by expenses and 
management fees that are charged against their assets as a 
theoretical unmanaged portfolio the sampp 500 incurs no such 
costs 
if you cant buy the sampp 500 you can buy shares in an index 
mutual fund set up to duplicate its performance as closely as 
possible while minimizing costs 
by its very nature an index fund will never achieve no 1 status 
in the fund performance rankings just as it will never finish at 
the back of the pack 
but over the past 12 months observes norman fosback editor of 
the advisory publication mutual fund forecaster index funds beat 
better than 80 percent of their competitors 
</TEXT>
