<TEXT>
the sandinista national liberation front won a 
bitter civil war in nicaragua 10 years ago that ended the 
42yearold somoza dynasty but the promise of the revolution is yet 
to be realized here is a report 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a decade has passed since july 19 
1979 when exuberant sandinista leaders rode into the city behind 
young guerrillas in makeshift uniforms who had driven out the 
entrenched somoza dictatorship 
how does nicaragua fare after a decade of revolution 
the sandinistas remain firmly in power despite determined us 
opposition but the people do not have a better life the economy is 
destitute some colleagues have joined the opposition and the soviet 
union has become less generous with aid 
there is sandinismo here for another 50 years an experienced 
south american diplomat said but a recent report said last years 
per capita gross national product was 300 
that would make nicaragua the western hemispheres poorest 
country a distinction long held by haiti and puts it in the same 
economic category as somalia sudan and other poor african nations 
with general elections only seven months away the organizational 
skills and popularity of the sandinista national liberation front 
face a tough test 
sandinismo has preserved its populist essence and the grassroots 
organization of a group that knows how angry citizens who feel they 
have nothing to lose can overthrow a government it is getting a 
negative message from some of those citizens 
i dont need to know about numbers said a managua woman who 
works as a domestic all i know is that every month things are 
getting worse weve been like this for 10 years these people dont 
know what theyre doing its time we had a change 
the gross national product figure was in a study commissioned by 
the sandinistas and underwritten by sweden that also said 
consumption had fallen by more than 70 percent since 1979 and the 
buying power of workers was down by more than 92 percent 
part of the study was presented in may to a conference of 16 
potential aid donors in stockholm president daniel ortega said 
nicaragua needed 250 million in aid for 1989 alone but left 
stockholm with only 50 million 
ortega denied nicaragua was among the worlds poorest nations he 
said studies by a us economist his government hired found all of 
latin america is undergoing a serious economic recession in which 
the standard of living has dropped to levels of 11 years ago 
the study sponsored by sweden recommends that some sandinista 
policies be reversed by halting land redistribution emphasizing 
private production and slashing the military education and health 
budgets 
there will be no reversal ortega said the revolutionary 
project continues 
he has traveled the country issuing land titles to tenant 
farmers his government confiscated the plantations of three growers 
who opposed the sandinistas and threatened to seize the land of 
other economic saboteurs 
lately progovernment news media have been recalling the civil 
war that brought victory in july 1979 
one photograph shows ortega and other guerrilla commanders guns 
slung on their shoulders riding into managua in a crowded jeep 48 
hours after president anastasio somoza had fled the country 
some guerrilla leaders and antisomoza politicians who celebrated 
on that day later left to fight again against the sandinistas 
among them was eden pastora the fabled commander zero who became 
the deputy defense minister but defected in 1981 to the 
ussupported contra guerrillas 
alfredo cesar president of the central bank left nicaragua on 
his honeymoon in 1982 and joined the directorate of the nicaraguan 
resistance the umbrella for antisandinista organizations in exile 
cesar returned a month ago as a member of the political opposition 
the most striking loss was of violeta barrios de chamorro widow 
of murdered publisher pedro joaquin chamorro who had been a foe of 
somoza chamorros assassination caused a groundswell of support for 
the sandinistas 
mrs chamorros family owns the newspaper la prensa now in 
opposition to the sandinistas she became a member of the first 
junta but resigned in april 1980 declaring the sandinista goals to 
be incompatible with her hopes for a democratic nicaragua 
current sandinista thinking seems to be that only a continuation 
of their populist policies will win the election yet some of those 
policies are alienating the private sector and pushing the economy 
deeper into crisis 
in past years sandinista leaders have said the very survival of 
their revolution was its greatest triumph 
a ussupported guerrilla war began two years after the 
revolution the sandinistas have survived the cutoff of 
international credits instigated by washington and the destruction 
wrought last october by hurricane joan which they estimated at 800 
million 
they have done so thanks in large part to aid from the soviet 
bloc and friends in northern europe notably sweden but that aid 
has diminished 
with declining aid and election impending the sandinistas have 
fallen back on one of their strengths organizing from the bottom up 
neighborhood groups known as sandinista defense committees had 
vanished because of resistance by the population but are being 
revived organizations of women youth and peasants are being 
strengthened 
</TEXT>
