<TEXT>
the writer a former central america 
correspondent now based in atlanta was in managua when the 
victorious sandinista guerrilla army entered the nicaraguan capital 
this is his account of that tumultuous day 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
ten years ago just before noon on a blisteringhot thursday the 
first jubilant ragtag column of sandinistas entered managua 
following their only tank down a side street to the bunker of ousted 
dictator anastasio somoza 
without firing a shot the guerrillas burst through the gate of 
the deserted military headquarters and swarmed into the bunker and 
supply sheds ending a bitter bloody revolution that brought the 
biggest change in central america since independence from spain 
somoza had fled to miami two days earlier leaving the country 
his family had ruled for 42 years in the hands of a caretaker 
president who also fled after only a few hours in office 
managua looked nearly empty the morning of july 19 1979 a day 
nicaraguans call simply the victory somozas soldiers aware 
that the sandinistas were only hours away had been deserting their 
positions all night abandoning weapons and vehicles donning 
civilian clothes blending into the population 
after dawn church bells on the outskirts began to ring the 
bells had signaled rebel victories in other towns and cities 
a group of government soldiers slipped into the lobby of the 
intercontinental hotel next to the military headquarters and 
peeled off the uniforms they wore over civilian clothes they left 
the uniforms weapons and other gear on the lobby floor 
most people stayed in their homes as that first column of about 
700 sandinista fighters from the northern city of leon walked by 
later in the day thousands more from rebelheld southern cities 
poured into the capital in commandeered government trucks 
inside somozas compound guerrillas threw down their old 
weapons shed tattered uniforms and outfitted themselves with new 
clothing 
a sandinista couple posed for pictures in somozas bed with a 
redandblack rebel flag draped over the headboard somoza had lived 
in the bunker for several weeks 
a tired guerrilla with holes in his boots found several cases of 
usmade crations and retired to somozas office put his feet on 
the desk under a portrait of the departed enemy and enjoyed a can of 
peaches he said it was his first food in two days 
managua became a madhouse that day the victors fired thousands 
of newly captured bullets into the air commandeered cars and 
painted them with sandinista slogans they freed hundreds of 
political and ordinary prisoners from jails in managua and nearby 
tipitapa 
wild shooting continued for two hours but miraculously no one 
was hit then a tropical downpour drenched and calmed the city 
daniel ortega the member of the fivemember sandinista junta who 
would become president arrived from costa rica at about 530 pm 
on friday july 20 when all had reached managua the junta 
members were given a tumultuous welcome in the main plaza by about 
500000 people a sandinista flag dangled from a statue atop the 
wrecked shell of managuas cathedral 
the civil war was over one nicaraguan in five was homeless and 
by red cross estimates about 45000 people had been killed 
reporters who entered somozas bunker before the guerrillas 
arrived found unfinished cups of coffee beside maps in the war room 
the generals hat worn by somoza a west point graduate was on its 
accustomed hook 
two partially packed suitcases had been left behind their 
contents halfscattered in the room 
somozas departure by private jet had long been a question of 
when not if 
the united states his main military supplier had stopped 
shipments and pressured others to do so by some accounts somoza 
could have defended his position for only about three weeks and 
lacked the arms to recapture any of the more than 25 cities held by 
the sandinistas 
with army casualties mounting and guerrilla forces growing he 
faced a manpower problem 
toward the end barefoot young men from the atlantic jungle 
region were being trucked into government training camps and sent 
out less than a week later to face seasoned disciplined guerrilla 
fighters in an uneven battle 
us ambassador lawrence pezzullo had been meeting almost daily 
with somoza arguing the hopelessness of the dictators situation 
somoza rarely left his bunker reporters kept an eye on it during 
the day but were prevented from doing so at night by a 7 pm 
shoottokill curfew 
on monday july 16 somozas prized parrots were brought in their 
cages to the bunker that night he met secretly with his national 
assembly and resigned 
an aide confirmed that somoza left for miami where he had an 
estate at 4 am on tuesday july 17 the aide fled a day later 
pezzullo moved to panama on wednesday with other key members of 
the us embassy staff 
now it was thursday morning july 19 and the church bells rang 
in the distance managua was without police or a government 
thousands of citizens were armed with rifles dropped by somozas 
soldiers no one was in charge 
many people who had not fired a shot in the war suddenly became 
sandinistas setting up freelance roadblocks and checkpoints armed 
with found weapons 
within a few years three of the five original junta members two 
nicaraguan ambassadors to washington and a top sandinista field 
commander had abandoned the new government some had joined the 
armed opposition 
the united states was financing and training the growing contra 
rebel movement and nicaragua was at war with itself again 
</TEXT>
