<TEXT>
corporate raider t boone pickens is one of the few 
americans to have experienced firsthand one of the stranger 
traditions of capitalism in japan the battle of sokaiya or 
professional hecklers versus loyal company employees at annual 
shareholders meetings 
the texas oilman is a major shareholder in a japanese auto parts 
maker called koito manufacturing co and when he came to tokyo last 
week he experienced the most unusual shareholders meeting ive 
ever attended in my life 
toughlooking men in flashy suits and tightly permed hair filled 
the room along with mildmannered employees in white shirts and 
neckties and the lone texan 
pickens made a pitch for increasing shareholders rights and 
improving profits 
a number of other shareholders backed him up but their style was 
different from pickens courteous drawl 
in threatening cadences reminiscent of movie yakuza or 
gangsters the sokaiya repeated some of pickens points threw in a 
bunch of their own and badgered the visibly shaken management of 
koito for an hour an a half 
hey you shouted one young man at the president of the 
company what kind of education are you giving your employees i 
passed 10 of them on the way in this morning and only two said good 
morning is that any way to treat a shareholder huh 
profits are down said another in tones so velvety it was 
almost scary it really doesnt appear that youre putting out 
much effort 
finally an older man who identified himself as part of the japan 
youth society an ultrarightwing group gave a virtuoso 
performance he began in a soft throaty voice like marlon brandos 
in the godfather and ended with a ringing gutterlanguage parody 
of pundits criticizing japans lack of international spirit and its 
recent scandals linking businessmen and politicians 
pickens later praised the hecklers i thought they asked some 
very good questions he said still he admitted thats an 
interesting way to ask for an income statement 
police say the sokaiya who use their legal rights as 
shareholders to attend meetings have ties to the underworld if 
they arent paid off they harrass management with endless questions 
and occasionally threaten violence employeeshareholders turn out 
in force to defend management against the attack 
the ritual battle between employees and shareholders symbolizes a 
basic conflict for japanese companies just who does the company 
belong to 
the traditional japanese notion is that it belongs to the 
management and employees who devote their lives to the company 
companies are very warm to their workers japanese capitalism 
has got almost communistic elements to it when you think about 
it says masakazu kobayashi one of japans few shareholders 
rights activists 
but by american concepts of capitalism and at least legally 
speaking in japan a company belongs to its owners in the case of a 
publicly listed company thats the shareholders 
as koitos largest shareholder pickens asked for representation 
on its board of directors though he owns onefifth of the company 
he was denied a seat 
now hes complaining to washington that americans dont have the 
same access to investment in japan as japanese have in the united 
states 
japanese businessmen admit they largely ignore individual 
shareholders domestic as well as foreign about 90 percent of 
companies hold shareholders meetings on the same day to discourage 
attendance dividends are widely considered money down the drain and 
are generally kept low 
but many japanese managers argue that emphasizing employees 
rather than owners and reinvesting in research and better factories 
rather than paying out dividends is the secret of their success 
pickens arguments won support in a number of editorials in 
leading newspapers pickens says that japan should increase 
shareholders rights in effect emphasize shortterm profits and 
encourage mergers and acquisitions because it would be good for 
the economy 
but many investors in the booming tokyo stock market have been 
making a killing in capital gains over the past few years and dont 
really care about having a voice in management or in collecting 
dividends 
pickens argues that managers have a responsibility to 
shareholders to show regular profit growth when a manager starts 
talking about investing in the longterm future i ask when is 
the payoff when is someday he said 
many japanese managers think ignoring quarterly profits for the 
long view is essential to growth and think pickens kind of 
impatience is what has led to an american failure to invest in the 
future 
finally pickens argues that weak shareholders lead to lazy 
unaccountable management poor corporate performance and a sluggish 
economy 
the problem is thats a little hard to see in japan 
</TEXT>
