princetonnewport partners sold and then bought 
back blocks of securities at the end of 1984 for the purchase price 
plus a consistent 625cent commission a federal prosecutor said in 
the first securities racketeering trial 
crossexamining former princetonnewport managing partner james 
sutton regan assistant us attorney mark hansen sought to 
demonstrate that the deals were prearranged and in violation of 
federal tax and securities laws 
regan one of six defendants in the case repeatedly denied that 
the partnership had contracts with investment firms to buy back 
securities at prearranged prices 
also charged are four other princetonnewport officials and a 
former drexel burnham lambert inc trader the case has attracted 
wide interest because the defendants were the first securities 
executives charged under the federal racketeer influenced and 
corrupt organizations law 
hansen listed a series of late december 1984 transactions in 
which princetonnewport sold corporate bonds to merrill lynch amp co 
and bought them back a few days later at the same price plus 116 
or 625 cents the deals were arranged by princetonnewport partner 
paul a berkman 
isnt it a fact that mr berkman was told up front that it was 
going to be 6 cents hansen asked 
i have no knowledge of that regan said 
the government is seeking to show that such a securities 
parking arrangement is illegal if it involved a predetermined 
buyback date and price hansen said the 625 cent increase in the 
buyback price indicated a set deal 
the indictment in the case contends princetonnewports 
executives engaged in a racketeering conspiracy through bogus 
securities trades to generate millions of dollars in false tax 
losses 
regan has testified the firm arranged securities transactions but 
without set buyback prices to generate shortterm losses for tax 
purposes he testified under questioning from his lawyer that he 
believed the deals were legal 
also on trial are princetonnewport general partners charles 
zarzecki and jack z rabinowitz the firms controller steven b 
smotrich and former drexel trader bruce lee newberg 
the jury trial is being held before us district judge robert 
carter 
princetonnewport was a small securities firm with offices in 
princeton nj and newport beach calif that went out of 
business after the indictment was brought last august 
