<TEXT>
washington state university researchers 
want to find out whether a japanese breed of cattle known as wagyu 
can be raised profitably in the united states 
a yes answer could mean high stakes to beef producers in 
washington and elsewhere who potentially could make hefty profits 
producing beef for the lucrative japanese restaurant market 
we are shipping some of our prime beef over there now said 
jerry reeves a wsu animal scientist involved in the wagyu project 
we get about 4 a pound for it their wagyu cattle bring in 10 to 
40 a pound 
the highest grade wagyu carcasses fetch as much as 16000 in 
japan about twice as much as the average carcass price in the 
united states reeves said in a news release this week 
its a niche market but at a different level there may be a 
market for wagyu crossbreds which japan cannot produce 
economically said ray wright a wsu animal physiologist heading 
the research project we also might have a market for wagyu beef 
in japanese restaurants in the united states 
the scientists want to find out if wagyu beef animals can be bred 
in the united states profitably to meet japanese preference for 
erxtremely tender cuts used in sukiyaki and other japanese dishes in 
which the beef is cooked in boiling water 
us beef carcasses are a poor substitute because the fat tends 
to concentrate on the outside whereas wagyu carcasses have a high 
degree of marbling in the muscle said wright 
if you drop our select grade beef into boiling water it comes 
out tough reeves added the interior fat of the wagyu beef 
protects it when it hits the water and makes it tender 
the wsu researchers have applied for permission to import live 
wagyu cattle embryos and semen from japan but wright said he is 
not optimistic about getting approval anytime soon 
you have to understand that the japanese control the market for 
wagyu right now he said i think theyll be reluctant to allow 
export of their animals 
as they await a response the scientists have been negotiating 
with a texas cattleman to buy a couple of wagyu heifers the owner 
might be the only person to possess wagyus outside of japan his 
animals are descendants of four wagyu bulls imported to the united 
states in the early 1970s 
once the scientists acquire some cattle they plan to breed them 
by embryo transfer processes that would be the first step in 
finding out exactly what us cattleman have to do to rear the 
cattle profitably 
even if they can gain access to the japanese market us beef 
producers will have to adapt their production systems to accommodate 
the japanese cattle the wsu researchers say 
us cattlemen feed large numbers of animals all they can eat 
to finish them out in 120 days reeves said japanese cattlemen 
he said feed no more than six wagyu at a time and dont market them 
until they are four years old 
well probably have to feed them the same amount of time 
reeves said but it wont be economical to massage the animals and 
feed them beer as is the custom in japan 
</TEXT>
