<TEXT>
japans world trade surplus narrowed 11 percent 
overall in june but continued to widen against its largest trading 
partner the united states finance ministry officials reported 
wednesday 
japan posted an unadjusted trade surplus of 5290 billion last 
month down from 5950 billion a year earlier but up from 3760 
billion in may 
the trade surplus with the united states grew 03 percent to 
3634 billion from 3622 billion a year earlier 
exports to the united states grew 79 percent to 7931 billion 
while imports from the united states rose 153 percent to 4297 
billion the report said 
the trade figures in june brought japans surplus in the first 
six months of 1989 to 3350 billion down slightly from 337 
billion in the same period last year 
ministry officials attributed the wider trade surplus from may to 
june to a 3percent consumption tax that forced importers to buy 
more before the new tax took effect april 1 
from a year earlier however both exports and imports showed 
moderate growth though imports grew faster 
exports of products like machinery nonferrous metals 
television sets video tape recorders and semiconductors were brisk 
while japan imported more of us goods such as meat lumber and 
pulp business machines audio equipment semiconductors 
nonferrous metals cars and steel 
steel imports from the united states for instance jumped 2124 
percent from the yearearlier month to 19768 billion 
in june the government report said the yen declined against the 
dollar making the value of yendenominated shipments smaller when 
calculated in dollar terms the dollar was valued at an average 
14306 yen in june a slight gain from 14306 yen a year earlier 
due to japans economic expansion that accompanied personal 
consumption and corporate equipment investment imports of 
manufactured goods remained strong accounting for 499 percent of 
overall imports in june 
in the first half of 1989 oil prices were generally lower 
although they began rising in may and june and pushed up overall 
import figures 
in addition to the introduction of the consumption tax finance 
ministry officials said the death of emperor hirohito in january 
and his funeral and other services in the following months dampened 
business activities of many companies and hurt the countrys trade 
</TEXT>
