<TEXT>
the fate of time inc rests in the hands 
of a delaware judge who must decide if the media giant can dismiss a 
122 billion hostile bid from paramount communications inc and 
proceed with its own 14 billion tender offer for warner 
communications inc 
on wall street which intently watched a delaware chancery court 
hearing tuesday for signs of how judge william t allen might rule 
traders were already betting that paramount would lose 
time stock skidded 637 a share to 14625 in new york stock 
exchange trading as allen heard arguments on requests by attorneys 
for paramount and some time shareholders for an injunction to block 
times 70ashare offer for warner 
the drop in times stock price indicated that pessimistic 
investors were taking whatever profits they could before allens 
ruling which is expected later this week 
in early trading today time stock recovered some ground moving 
up 3 a share to 14925 analysts said the gain likely was a 
response to tuesdays sharp declne 
warner stock was down 25 cents to 6262 a share in early 
trading today and paramount was up 25 cents to 5825 a share 
the attorneys for paramount and the shareholders contended 
tuesday that times directors violated their duty in refusing to let 
shareholders vote on paramounts 200ashare bid 
the lawyers claimed that the time board effectively put the 
company up for sale when it agreed to a stockswap merger with 
warner in march under delaware law if a company is up for sale 
its board must entertain any bids that would fetch the most money 
for shareholders 
melvyn cantor representing paramount charged that time 
officials knew they were opening the company up to possible bids 
when they included a provision in the merger agreement with warner 
calling for an exchange of stock between the two companies 
michael r klein an attorney representing texas investor robert 
m bass and other major time shareholders said the exchange was 
done to defend the transaction 
klein said of times directors when they made that choice to 
pursue the merger with warner they were quite substantially aware 
that the marketplace would supply alternatives 
time attorney robert joffee dismissed kleins arguments the 
mere possibility that someone might make a bid even the making of 
a bid does not put a company into play he said 
the paramount and shareholder attorneys repeatedly asked allen to 
allow the holders of time stock to vote on the paramount offer 
sherri r savett also representing stockholders argued that 
they should be allowed to vote on the two offers because they stood 
to lose a lot of money if the timewarner merger succeeded and the 
paramount bid failed 
joffee countered that if the paramount offer does fall through 
it would happen because paramounts bid remains subject to a number 
of conditions including obtaining regulatory approvals to operate 
times cable television systems 
warner attorney charles richards said it was warner and not 
paramount shareholders who had the most to lose the failure of the 
time bid would send warner stock tumbling and open the company up to 
an unwanted bid richards said 
time and warner had planned to submit their original merger plan 
to their shareholders but the companies changed the agreement in 
response to the paramount bid to the tender offer by time for 
warner stock 
the attorneys for time and warner told the judge the directors 
did not violate their duty to shareholders because delaware law does 
not require the board to submit either paramounts offer or the 
warner bid to a vote 
joffee contended the company never was for sale he said the 
proposed merger of time and warner was the result of longterm 
business planning and said the law did not require the company to 
shift its strategy because it receives an apparently lucrative bid 
he said time also doesnt have to submit the warner deal to a 
vote because it does not require the dilution of time stock 
the courtroom was filled to overflowing with 120 spectators 
mostly reporters and stock arbitragers who are speculating on the 
outcome of the takeover battle many stood against walls or crouched 
in the aisles 
the crowd was so big that about 30 people were shut out and 
forced to wait in the hallway and it so strained the air 
conditioning system that allen invited lawyers at one point in the 
5hour hearing to take off their jackets 
many arbitragers were unable to confer with their offices during 
the hearing because they were not allowed to bring cellular 
telephones into the courtroom and couldnt leave the room for fear 
of losing their place to someone from the hallway 
allens decision which undoubtedly will be appealed to delaware 
supreme court could decide the outcome of the threeway struggle 
for time and could affect the future of friendly mergers in the 
future as many of the nations largest companies are incorporated 
here 
