<TEXT>
hasbro inc said wednesday it had 
completed the purchase of most of the product lines of financially 
troubled coleco industries inc and would immediately begin 
producing the popular cabbage patch kids dolls 
hasbro the nations largest toymaker agreed last week to 
purchase colecos major assets for 85 million cash and an option 
for coleco to purchase 1 million shares of pawtucketbased hasbro at 
2885 each after its bankruptcy reorganization plan was confirmed 
said barry alperin hasbros executive vice president 
conneticutbased coleco filed for protection from its creditors 
under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy act a year ago citing 
debts of 5403 million 
hasbro stock closed at 20 wednesday on the american stock 
exchange down 25 cents a share 
hasbro said it had reached agreement with appalachian artworks 
inc creator of cabbage patch kids to begin manufacturing the 
dolls immediately in time to advertise them for christmas 
the dolls would be made overseas and packaged at hasbros milton 
bradley division in east longmeadow mass alperin said most of 
colecos other lines including the scrabble and parcheesi games 
also would be produced in massachusetts 
hasbro which also bought the right to use colecos name would 
discontinue some of its products including alf and wrinkles 
alperin said 
chairman alan g hassenfeld said the acquisition would add some 
timetested products which will enrich hasbros three divisions 
without material additions to our cost structure 
hasbros third division is playskool 
alperin said the cabbage patch line which was the largest 
selling toy of all time in 1985 has not had the attention it 
deserved over the past couple of years 
sales of cabbage patch peaked at more than 600 million in 1985 
but slipped to 58 million by last year 
</TEXT>
