<TEXT>
dunkin donuts inc charged wednesday in a federal 
lawsuit that two canadian companies have made false and misleading 
statements about their financing for a 305 million bid to take over 
the doughnut chain 
in an amended complaint in us district court in boston dunkin 
donuts alleged that the financing arranged by unicorp canada corp 
and cara operations ltd would not meet federal margin regulations 
which limit borrowing to buy stock 
the board of directors of the randolphbased doughnut chain also 
issued a statement contending that the financing for the hostile 
tender offer of 43 a share was preliminary and subject to 
substantial conditions 
dunkin donuts continues to urge shareholders to reject the 
highly conditional illusory and inadequate offer the statement 
said 
a spokesman for the canadian companies said the allegations by 
dunkin donuts were totally baseless 
the spokesman elan sober said the companies discussed the offer 
with federal regulators in washington and that the companies are 
satisfied that it complies fully with all applicable laws including 
the us margin regulations 
unicorp a torontobased real estate banking and energy firm 
holds about 12 percent of dunkin donuts common stock it formed a 
partnership with cara a food services company to launch the 
hostile offer on june 15 
kingsbridge capital group a subsidiary of unicorp and cara have 
said they would invest up to 80 million of equity and debt in the 
takeover and have a firm commitment for an additional 275 million 
of financing from trilon financial group and great lakes group inc 
both of toronto 
the commitment letter is a firm written commitment to lend by 
two major canadian financial institutions said sober its 
conditions are entirely standard there is nothing preliminary about 
it 
</TEXT>
